{"author":{"id":"d090680751e9d81548e628ee372337dbb14df0993593a8afe125eaa85e30d5d8"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1706050996,"nonce":"AYfGafJI5qMpOAUjQMF7tTkbRAs=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOAW4Y0s58_6mc","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5729","origin":"github"},"title":"Infer collection element naming with `default_identifier_source`","message":"When collections are created as a tool output, the Galaxy tool author can declare output element names by referencing input datasets. However, this feature is poorly documented and seems to be used in only one IUC tool. Its use is relevant for any tool that accepts paired inputs and produces paired outputs. Without this declaration, Galaxy will default to naming output collection elements after the first input dataset element. This results in \"R2\" outputs being named as \"R1\" which is obviously misleading and confusing for the user. \n\nAs described in issue https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5703:\n\n![image](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/assets/42562517/0246723d-c231-48c0-9a3d-2b9f7e61d2ce)\n\n1. The Trimmomatic job was submitted with paired reads in two collections: R1 and R2\n2. The job outputs four collections: Unpaired R1, Unpaired R2, Paired R1, Paired R2\n3. In the screenshot above the \"Unpaired R2\" collection is selected in the History\n4. Note the input files `gah.fastqsanger` (R1) and `GSM461181_2.fastqsanger` (R2)\n5. Now look at the first element in the History. It has been named after the first input dataset in the job (R1), and not after `${readtype.fastq_r2_in.name}` (highlighted in Dataset info panel) as I would have expected.\n6. The result is that the `XXX_R2.fastqsanger` files are being named `XXX_R1.fastqsanger` which looks like a bug?\n\nThis issue refers to trimmomatic, which has been fixed by https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/pull/5728.","files":null}]}